      <p><font size="5" color="green">Friday (Apr 7, 2023), 4:30-5:30 pm: <a href="http://maths.nju.edu.cn/~zwsun/">Zhi-Wei Sun</a> (Nanjing University)</font></p>
      <pubtit><font size="4">A new result similar to the Graham-Pollak theorem</font></pubtit>
      <p><em><strong>Abstract: </strong></em>In 1971, R.L. Graham and H.O. Pollak obtained a beautiful result on determinants of distance matrices for trees. In this talk, we introduce the speakerâ€™s recent work which is similar to the Graham-Pollak theorem. Namely, we will prove the following result:Let $n &gt; 1$ be an integer, and let $T$ be any tree with $n+1$ vertices $v_1,\ldots,v_{n+1}$, where $v_1$ and $v_{n+1}$ are two leaves of $T$. Then \(\det[q^{d(v_{j+1},v_k)}-t]_{1\le j,k\le n}=t(q-1)^n(q+1)^{n-2},\) where $d(v_{j+1},v_k)$ is the distance between $v_{j+1}$ and $v_k$ in the tree $T$.</p>
